# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-telemetry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] The IPFIX standards requirements were outlined in the original RFC 3917.
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] Cisco NetFlow Version 9 was the basis for IPFIX.
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] The basic specifications for IPFIX are documented in RFC 7011 through RFC 7015, and RFC 5103.
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] A pool of **Metering Processes** collects data packets at one or more **Observation Points**, optionally filters them and aggregates information about these packets.
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] An **Exporter** then gathers each of the Observation Points together into an **Observation Domain** and sends this information via the IPFIX protocol to a **Collector**.
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] Exporters and Collectors are in a many-to-many relationship: One Exporter can send data to many Collectors and one Collector can receive data from many Exporters.
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] Similar to the NetFlow Protocol, IPFIX considers a **flow** to be any number of packets observed in a specific timeslot and sharing a number of properties, e.g.
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] "**same source, same destination, same protocol**".
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] Using IPFIX, devices like routers can inform a central monitoring station about their view of a potentially larger network.
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] IPFIX is a **push protocol**, i.e. each sender will periodically send IPFIX messages to configured receivers without any interaction by the receiver.
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] The actual makeup of data in IPFIX messages is to a great extent up to the sender.
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] IPFIX introduces the makeup of these messages to the receiver with the help of special **Templates**.
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] The sender is also free to use user-defined data types in its messages, so the protocol is freely extensible and can adapt to different scenarios.
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] IPFIX prefers the Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP) as its transport layer protocol, but also allows the use of the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) or User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] As can be seen, the message contains the IPFIX header and two IPFIX Sets: One Template Set that introduces the build-up of the Data Set used, as well as one Data Set, which contains the actual data.
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] When IPFIX is sent over a protocol which keeps a session state (TCP or SCTP), the Template Set need not be retransmitted since it is buffered in Collectors.
[src:network-telemetry/ip-flow-information-export] Since the Template Set can change over time, it must be retransmitted if a new session state is established or if IPFIX is sent over UDP which is a session-less protocol.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Routers and switches that support NetFlow can collect IP traffic statistics on all interfaces where NetFlow is enabled, and later export those statistics as NetFlow records toward at least one NetFlow collector—typically a server that does the actual traffic analysis.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Note that the Egress interface, IP Nexthop or BGP Nexthops are not part of the key, and may not be accurate if the route changes before the expiration of the flow, or if load-balancing is done per-packet.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] This definition of flows is also used for IPv6, and a similar definition is used for MPLS and Ethernet flows.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Advanced NetFlow or IPFIX implementations like Cisco Flexible NetFlow allow user-defined flow keys.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] The router will output a flow record when it determines that the flow is finished.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] It does this by flow aging: when the router sees new traffic for an existing flow it resets the aging counter.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Also, TCP session termination in a TCP flow causes the router to expire the flow.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Routers can also be configured to output a flow record at a fixed interval even if the flow is still ongoing.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] NetFlow records are traditionally exported using User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and collected using a NetFlow collector.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] The IP address of the NetFlow collector and the destination UDP port must be configured on the sending router.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] A common value is UDP port 2055, but other values like 9555 or 9995, 9025, 9026 etc. can also be used.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] For efficiency reasons, the router traditionally does not keep track of flow records already exported, so if a NetFlow packet is dropped due to network congestion or packet corruption, all contained records are lost forever.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] The UDP protocol does not inform the router of the loss so it can send the packets again.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] This can be a real problem, especially with NetFlow v8 or v9 that can aggregate a lot of packets or flows into a single record.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] A single UDP packet loss can cause a huge impact on the statistics of some flows.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] That is why some modern implementations of NetFlow use the Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP) to export packets so as to provide some protection against packet loss, and make sure that NetFlow v9 templates are received before any related record is exported.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Note that TCP would not be suitable for NetFlow because a strict ordering of packets would cause excessive buffering and delays.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] The problem with SCTP is that it requires interaction between each NetFlow collector and each router exporting NetFlow.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] There may be performance limitations if a router has to deal with many NetFlow collectors, and a NetFlow collector has to deal with many routers, especially when some of them are unavailable due to failure or maintenance.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] SCTP may not be efficient if NetFlow must be exported toward several independent collectors, some of which may be test servers that can go down at any moment.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] UDP allows simple replication of NetFlow packets using Network taps or L2 or L3 Mirroring.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Simple stateless equipment can also filter or change the destination address of NetFlow UDP packets if necessary.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Since NetFlow export almost only use network backbone links, packet loss will often be negligible.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] If it happens, it will mostly be on the link between the network and the NetFlow collectors.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] A NetFlow record can contain a wide variety of information about the traffic in a given flow.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] For ICMP flows, the Source Port is zero, and the Destination Port number field codes ICMP message Type and Code (port = ICMP-Type * 256 + ICMP-Code) .
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] The source and destination Autonomous System (AS) number fields can report the destination AS (last AS of AS-Path) or the immediate neighbor AS (first AS of AS-Path) depending on the router configuration.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] But the AS number will be zero if the feature is not supported, the route is unknown or not announced by BGP, or the AS is the local AS.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] There is no explicit way to distinguish between these cases.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] By analyzing flow data, a picture of traffic flow and traffic volume in a network can be built.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] The NetFlow record format has evolved over time, hence the inclusion of version numbers.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Cisco maintains details of the different version numbers and the layout of the packets for each version.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] NetFlow is usually enabled on a per-interface basis to limit load on the router components involved in NetFlow, or to limit the amount of NetFlow records exported.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] NetFlow usually captures all packets received by an ingress IP interface, but some NetFlow implementations use IP filters to decide if a packet can be observed by NetFlow.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Some NetFlow implementations also allow the observation of packets on the egress IP interface, but this must be used with care: all flows from any ingress interface with NetFlow enabled to any interface with NetFlow enabled could be counted twice.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Standard NetFlow was designed to process all IP packets on an interface.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] But in some environments, e.g. on Internet backbones, that was too costly, due to the extra processing required for each packet, and large number of simultaneous flows.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] So Cisco introduced sampled NetFlow on Cisco 12000, and that is now used in all high-end routers that implement NetFlow.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Only one packet out of *n* is processed, where *n*, the sampling rate, is determined by the router configuration.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Some implementations have more complex methods to sample packets, like per-flow sampling on Cisco Catalysts.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] The sampling rate is often the same for all interfaces, but can be adjusted per interface for some routers.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] When Sampled NetFlow is used, the NetFlow records must be adjusted for the effect of sampling - traffic volumes, in particular, are now an estimate rather than the actual measured flow volume.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] NetFlow was initially implemented by Cisco, and described in an "informational" document that was not on the standards track: RFC 3954 – Cisco Systems NetFlow Services Export Version 9.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] The NetFlow protocol itself has been superseded by Internet Protocol Flow Information eXport (IPFIX).
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Based on the NetFlow Version 9 implementation, IPFIX is on the IETF standards track with RFC 5101 (obsoleted by RFC 7011), RFC 5102 (obsoleted by RFC 7012), etc. which were published in 2008.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Many vendors other than Cisco provide similar network flow monitoring technology.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] NetFlow may be a prevalent name in the area of flow monitoring, because of Cisco dominant market share in the networking industry.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Also flow-tools collection of software allows to process and manage NetFlow exports from Cisco and Juniper routers.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Introduced with the launch of the Cisco ASA 5580 products, NetFlow Security Event Logging utilizes NetFlow v9 fields and templates in order to efficiently deliver security telemetry in high performance environments.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] NetFlow Security Event Logging scales better than syslog while offering the same level of detail and granularity in logged events.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] NetFlow collection using standalone NetFlow probes is an alternative to flow collection from routers and switches.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] This approach can overcome some limitations of router-based NetFlow monitoring.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] The probes are transparently connected to the monitored link as a passive appliance using the TAP or SPAN port of the appliance.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Historically, NetFlow monitoring is easier to implement in a dedicated probe than in a router.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] The easiest way to address the above drawbacks is to use a packet capture appliance inline in front of the router and capture all of the NetFlow output from the router.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] This method allows for storage of large amount of NetFlow data (typically many years worth of data) and does not require reconfiguration of the network.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] NetFlow collection from dedicated probes is well suited for observation of critical links, whereas NetFlow on routers provides a Network-wide view of the traffic that can be used for capacity planning, accounting, performance monitoring, and security.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] NetFlow was originally a Cisco packet switching technology for Cisco routers, implemented in IOS 11.x around 1996.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] It was originally a software implementation for the Cisco 7000, 7200 and 7500, where it was thought as an improvement over the then current Cisco Fast Switching.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Netflow was invented by Darren Kerr and Barry Bruin from Cisco (U.S. patent # 6,243,667 ).
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] The idea was that the first packet of a flow would create a NetFlow switching record.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] This record would then be used for all later packets of the same flow, until the expiration of the flow.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] Only the first packet of a flow would require an investigation of the route table to find the most specific matching route.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] This is an expensive operation in software implementations, especially the old ones without Forwarding information base.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] The NetFlow switching record was actually some kind of route cache record, and old versions of IOS still refer to the NetFlow cache as **ip route-cache**.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] This technology was advantageous for local networks.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] This was especially true if some of the traffic had to be filtered by an ACL as only the first packet of a flow had to be evaluated by the ACL.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] As a switching technology, NetFlow was replaced around 1995 by Cisco Express Forwarding.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] This first appeared on Cisco 12000 routers, and later replaced NetFlow switching on advanced IOS for the Cisco 7200 and Cisco 7500.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] As of 2012, technologies similar to NetFlow switching are still in use in most firewalls and software-based IP routers.
[src:network-telemetry/netflow] For instance the conntrack feature of the Netfilter framework used by Linux.
[src:network-telemetry/network-management] A number of applications and protocols exist to support network and network device management.
[src:network-telemetry/network-management] Network management allows IT professionals to monitor network components within a large network area.
[src:network-telemetry/network-management] Access methods include the SNMP, command-line interface (CLI), custom XML, CMIP, Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI), Transaction Language 1 (TL1), CORBA, NETCONF, RESTCONF and the Java Management Extensions (JMX).
[src:network-telemetry/network-management] Schemas include the Structure of Management Information (SMI), YANG, WBEM, the Common Information Model (CIM Schema), and MTOSI amongst others.
[src:network-telemetry/network-management] Effective network management can provide positive strategic impacts.
[src:network-telemetry/network-management] For example, in the case of developing an infrastructure, providing participants with some interactive space allows them to collaborate with each other, thereby promoting overall benefits.
[src:network-telemetry/network-management] At the same time, the value of network management to the strategic network is also affected by the relationship between participants.
[src:network-telemetry/network-management] Active participation, interaction and collaboration can make them more trusting of each other and enhance cohesion.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] There are many different ways to measure the performance of a network, as each network is different in nature and design.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] Performance can also be modeled and simulated instead of measured; one example of this is using state transition diagrams to model queuing performance or to use a Network Simulator.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] The available channel bandwidth and achievable signal-to-noise ratio determine the maximum possible throughput.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] It is not generally possible to send more data than dictated by the Shannon-Hartley Theorem.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] The *Time Window* is the period over which the throughput is measured.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] The choice of an appropriate time window will often dominate calculations of throughput, and whether latency is taken into account or not will determine whether the latency affects the throughput or not.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] The speed of light imposes a minimum propagation time on all electromagnetic signals.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] where s is the distance and cm is the speed of light in the medium (roughly 200,000 km/s for most fiber or electrical media, depending on their velocity factor).
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] This approximately means an additional millisecond round-trip delay (RTT) per 100 km (or 62 miles) of distance between hosts.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] Other delays also occur in intermediate nodes.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] In packet switched networks delays can occur due to queueing.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] In digital transmission, the number of **bit errors** is the number of received bits of a data stream over a communication channel that have been altered due to noise, interference, distortion or bit synchronization errors.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] The **bit error rate** or **bit error ratio** (**BER**) is the number of bit errors divided by the total number of transferred bits during a studied time interval.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] BER is a unitless performance measure, often expressed as a percentage.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] The **bit error probability** *pe* is the expectation value of the BER.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] The BER can be considered as an approximate estimate of the bit error probability.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] This estimate is accurate for a long time interval and a high number of bit errors.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] All of the factors above, coupled with user requirements and user perceptions, play a role in determining the perceived 'fastness' or utility, of a network connection.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] The relationship between throughput, latency, and user experience is most aptly understood in the context of a shared network medium, and as a scheduling problem.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] For some systems, latency and throughput are coupled entities.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] In TCP/IP, latency can also directly affect throughput.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] In TCP connections, the large bandwidth-delay product of high latency connections, combined with relatively small TCP window sizes on many devices, effectively causes the throughput of a high latency connection to drop sharply with latency.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] This can be remedied with various techniques, such as increasing the TCP congestion window size, or more drastic solutions, such as packet coalescing, TCP acceleration, and forward error correction, all of which are commonly used for high latency satellite links.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] TCP acceleration converts the TCP packets into a stream that is similar to UDP.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] Because of this, the TCP acceleration software must provide its own mechanisms to ensure the reliability of the link, taking the latency and bandwidth of the link into account, and both ends of the high latency link must support the method used.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] In the Media Access Control (MAC) layer, performance issues such as throughput and end-to-end delay are also addressed.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] Many systems can be characterized as dominated either by throughput limitations or by latency limitations in terms of end-user utility or experience.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] In some cases, hard limits such as the speed of light present unique problems to such systems and nothing can be done to correct this.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] Other systems allow for significant balancing and optimization for best user experience.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] A telecom satellite in geosynchronous orbit imposes a path length of at least 71000 km between transmitter and receiver. which means a minimum delay between message request and message receipt, or latency of 473 ms.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] This delay can be very noticeable and affects satellite phone service regardless of available throughput capacity.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] These long path length considerations are exacerbated when communicating with space probes and other long-range targets beyond Earth's atmosphere.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] The Deep Space Network implemented by NASA is one such system that must cope with these problems.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] Largely latency driven, the GAO has criticized the current architecture.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] Several different methods have been proposed to handle the intermittent connectivity and long delays between packets, such as delay-tolerant networking.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] At interstellar distances, the difficulties in designing radio systems that can achieve any throughput at all are massive.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] In these cases, maintaining communication is a bigger issue than how long that communication takes.
[src:network-telemetry/network-performance] Transportation is concerned almost entirely with throughput, which is why physical deliveries of backup tape archives are still largely done by vehicle.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP is widely used in network management for network monitoring.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP exposes management data in the form of variables on the managed systems organized in a management information base (MIB), which describes the system status and configuration.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] These variables can then be remotely queried (and, in some circumstances, manipulated) by network management applications.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Three significant versions of SNMP have been developed and deployed.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 is the original version of the protocol.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] More recent versions, SNMPv2c and SNMPv3, feature improvements in performance, flexibility and security.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP is a component of the Internet Protocol Suite as defined by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] It consists of a set of standards for network management, including an application layer protocol, a database schema, and a set of data objects.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] In typical uses of SNMP, one or more administrative computers called *managers* have the task of monitoring or managing a group of hosts or devices on a computer network.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Each managed system executes a software component called an *agent* that reports information via SNMP to the manager.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] A *managed device* is a network node that implements an SNMP interface that allows unidirectional (read-only) or bidirectional (read and write) access to node-specific information.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Managed devices exchange node-specific information with the NMSs.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Sometimes called network elements, the managed devices can be any type of device, including, but not limited to, routers, access servers, switches, cable modems, bridges, hubs, IP telephones, IP video cameras, computer hosts, and printers.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] An *agent* is a network-management software module that resides on a managed device.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] An agent has local knowledge of management information and translates that information to or from an SNMP-specific form.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] A *network management station* executes applications that monitor and control managed devices.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] NMSs provide the bulk of the processing and memory resources required for network management.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] One or more NMSs may exist on any managed network.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP agents expose management data on the managed systems as variables.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The protocol also permits active management tasks, such as configuration changes, through remote modification of these variables.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The variables accessible via SNMP are organized in hierarchies.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP itself does not define which variables a managed system should offer.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Rather, SNMP uses an extensible design that allows applications to define their own hierarchies.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] These hierarchies are described as a management information base (MIB).
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] MIBs describe the structure of the management data of a device subsystem; they use a hierarchical namespace containing object identifiers (OID).
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Each OID identifies a variable that can be read or set via SNMP.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] MIBs use the notation defined by Structure of Management Information Version 2.0 (SMIv2, RFC 2578), a subset of ASN.1.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP operates in the application layer of the Internet protocol suite.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] All SNMP messages are transported via User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The SNMP agent receives requests on UDP port 161.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The manager may send requests from any available source port to port 161 in the agent.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The agent response is sent back to the source port on the manager.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The manager receives notifications (*Traps* and *InformRequests*) on port 162.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The agent may generate notifications from any available port.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] When used with Transport Layer Security or Datagram Transport Layer Security, requests are received on port 10161 and notifications are sent to port 10162.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 specifies five core protocol data units (PDUs).
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Two other PDUs, *GetBulkRequest* and *InformRequest* were added in SNMPv2 and the *Report* PDU was added in SNMPv3.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] A manager-to-agent request to retrieve the value of a variable or list of variables.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Desired variables are specified in variable bindings (the value field is not used).
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] A manager-to-agent request to change the value of a variable or list of variables.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Variable bindings are specified in the body of the request.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Changes to all specified variables are to be made as an atomic operation by the agent.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] with (current) new values for the variables is returned.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] A manager-to-agent request to discover available variables and their values.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Rows of a table can be read by specifying column OIDs in the variable bindings of the request.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] with multiple variable bindings walked from the variable binding or bindings in the request.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] fields are used to control response behavior.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Asynchronous notification from agent to manager.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] While in other SNMP communication, the manager actively requests information from the agent, these are PDUs that are sent from the agent to the manager without being explicitly requested.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] enable an agent to notify the management station of significant events by way of an unsolicited SNMP message.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] value, an OID identifying the type of trap and optional variable bindings.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Destination addressing for traps is determined in an application-specific manner, typically through trap configuration variables in the MIB.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] fixes this as an acknowledgement is returned on receipt.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] RFC 1157 specifies that an SNMP implementation must accept a message of at least 484 bytes in length.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] In practice, SNMP implementations accept longer messages.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] If implemented correctly, an SNMP message is discarded if the decoding of the message fails and thus malformed SNMP requests are ignored.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] A successfully decoded SNMP request is then authenticated using the community string.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] If the authentication fails, a trap is generated indicating an authentication failure and the message is dropped.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 and SNMPv2c use *communities* to establish trust between managers and agents.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Most agents support three community names, one each for read-only, read-write and trap.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] These three *community strings* control different types of activities.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The read-only community applies to *get* requests.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The read-write community string applies to *set* requests.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The trap community string applies to receipt of *traps*.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 also uses community strings, but allows for secure authentication and communication between SNMP manager and agent.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] In practice, SNMP implementations often support multiple versions: typically SNMPv1, SNMPv2c, and SNMPv3.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP version 1 (SNMPv1) is the initial implementation of the SNMP protocol.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The design of SNMPv1 was done in the 1980s by a group of collaborators who viewed the officially sponsored OSI/IETF/NSF (National Science Foundation) effort (HEMS/CMIS/CMIP) as both unimplementable in the computing platforms of the time as well as potentially unworkable.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP was approved based on a belief that it was an interim protocol needed for taking steps towards large-scale deployment of the Internet and its commercialization.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 is widely used and is the de facto network management protocol in the Internet community.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 may be carried by transport layer protocols such as User Datagram Protocol (UDP), OSI Connectionless-mode Network Service (CLNS), AppleTalk Datagram Delivery Protocol (DDP), and Novell Internetwork Packet Exchange (IPX).
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Version 1 has been criticized for its poor security.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] For example, an organization may consider their internal network to be sufficiently secure that no encryption is necessary for its SNMP messages.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] In such cases, the *community name*, which is transmitted in cleartext, tends to be viewed as a de facto password, in spite of the original specification.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv2, defined by RFC 1441 and RFC 1452, revises version 1 and includes improvements in the areas of performance, security and manager-to-manager communications.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] It introduced *GetBulkRequest*, an alternative to iterative GetNextRequests for retrieving large amounts of management data in a single request.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The new party-based security system introduced in SNMPv2, viewed by many as overly complex, was not widely adopted.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] This version of SNMP reached the Proposed Standard level of maturity, but was deemed obsolete by later versions.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP version 2 introduces the option for 64-bit data counters.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Version 1 was designed only with 32-bit counters, which can store integer values from zero to 4.29 billion (precisely 4294967295).
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] A 32-bit version 1 counter cannot store the maximum speed of a 10-gigabit or larger interface, expressed in bits per second.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Similarly, a 32-bit counter tracking statistics for a 10-gigabit or larger interface can roll over back to zero again in less than one minute, which may be a shorter time interval than a counter is polled to read its current state.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] This would result in lost or invalid data due to the undetected value rollover and corruption of trend-tracking data.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The 64-bit version 2 counter can store values from zero to 18.4 quintillion (precisely 18,446,744,073,709,551,615) and so is currently unlikely to experience a counter rollover between polling events.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] For example, 1.6 terabit Ethernet is predicted to become available by 2025.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] A 64-bit counter incrementing at a rate of 1.6 trillion bits per second would be able to retain information for such an interface without rolling over for 133 days.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv2c is incompatible with SNMPv1 in two key areas: message formats and protocol operations.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv2c messages use a different header and different protocol data unit (PDU) formats than SNMPv1 messages.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv2c also uses two protocol operations that are not specified in SNMPv1.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] To overcome incompatibility, RFC 3584 defines two SNMPv1/v2c coexistence strategies: proxy agents and bilingual network-management systems.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] An SNMPv2 agent can act as a proxy agent on behalf of SNMPv1-managed devices.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] When an SNMPv2 NMS issues a command intended for an SNMPv1 agent, it sends it to the SNMPv2 proxy agent instead.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The proxy agent forwards `Get`, `GetNext`, and `Set` messages to the SNMPv1 agent unchanged.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] `GetBulk` messages are converted by the proxy agent to `GetNext` messages and then are forwarded to the SNMPv1 agent.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Additionally, the proxy agent receives and maps SNMPv1 trap messages to SNMPv2 trap messages and then forwards them to the NMS.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Bilingual SNMPv2 network-management systems support both SNMPv1 and SNMPv2.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] To support this dual-management environment, a management application examines information stored in a local database to determine whether the agent supports SNMPv1 or SNMPv2.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Based on the information in the database, the NMS communicates with the agent using the appropriate version of SNMP.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Although SNMPv3 makes no changes to the protocol aside from the addition of cryptographic security, it looks very different due to new textual conventions, concepts, and terminology.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The most visible change was to define a secure version of SNMP, by adding security and remote configuration enhancements to SNMP.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The security aspect is addressed by offering both strong authentication and data encryption for privacy.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] For the administration aspect, SNMPv3 focuses on two parts, namely notification originators and proxy forwarders.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The changes also facilitate remote configuration and administration of the SNMP entities, as well as addressing issues related to the large-scale deployment, accounting, and fault management.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Security was one of the biggest weaknesses of SNMP until v3.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Authentication in SNMP Versions 1 and 2 amounts to nothing more than a password (community string) sent in clear text between a manager and agent.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Each SNMPv3 message contains security parameters that are encoded as an octet string.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The meaning of these security parameters depends on the security model being used.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] v3 also defines the USM and VACM, which were later followed by a transport security model (TSM) that provided support for SNMPv3 over SSH and SNMPv3 over TLS and DTLS.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] As of 2004 the IETF recognizes *Simple Network Management Protocol version 3* as defined by RFC 3411–RFC 3418 (also known as STD0062) as the current standard version of SNMP.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The IETF has designated SNMPv3 a full Internet standard, the highest maturity level for an RFC.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] It considers earlier versions to be obsolete (designating them variously *Historic* or *Obsolete*).
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Some SNMP values (especially tabular values) require specific knowledge of table indexing schemes, and these index values are not necessarily consistent across platforms.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Some major equipment vendors tend to over-extend their proprietary command line interface (CLI) centric configuration and control systems.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] In February 2002 the Carnegie Mellon Software Engineering Institute (CM-SEI) Computer Emergency Response Team Coordination Center (CERT-CC) issued an Advisory on SNMPv1, after the Oulu University Secure Programming Group conducted a thorough analysis of SNMP message handling.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Most SNMP implementations, regardless of which version of the protocol they support, use the same program code for decoding protocol data units (PDU) and problems were identified in this code.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Other problems were found with decoding SNMP trap messages received by the SNMP management station or requests received by the SNMP agent on the network device.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Many vendors had to issue patches for their SNMP implementations.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Because SNMP is designed to allow administrators to monitor and configure network devices remotely, it can also be used to penetrate a network.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] A significant number of software tools can scan the entire network using SNMP; therefore, mistakes in the configuration of the read-write mode can make a network susceptible to attacks.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] In 2001, Cisco released information that indicated that, even in read-only mode, the SNMP implementation of Cisco IOS is vulnerable to certain denial of service attacks.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] These security issues can be fixed through an IOS upgrade.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] If SNMP is not used in a network, it should be disabled in network devices.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] When configuring SNMP read-only mode, close attention should be paid to the configuration of the access control and from which IP addresses SNMP messages are accepted.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] If the SNMP servers are identified by their IP addresses, SNMP is only allowed to respond to these IPs and SNMP messages from other IP addresses would be denied.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] However, IP address spoofing remains a security concern.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP is available in different versions, and each version has its own security issues.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v1 sends passwords in plaintext over the network.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Therefore, passwords can be read with packet sniffing.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v2 allows password hashing with MD5, but this has to be configured.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Virtually all network management software support SNMP v1, but not necessarily SNMP v2 or v3.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v2 was specifically developed to provide data security, that is authentication, privacy and authorization, but only SNMP version 2c gained the endorsement of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF), while versions 2u and 2* failed to gain IETF approval due to security issues.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v3 uses MD5, Secure Hash Algorithm (SHA) and keyed algorithms to offer protection against unauthorized data modification and spoofing attacks.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] If a higher level of security is needed the Data Encryption Standard (DES) can be optionally used in the cipher block chaining mode.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v3 is implemented on Cisco IOS since release 12.0(3)T.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 may be subject to brute force and dictionary attacks for guessing the authentication keys, or encryption keys, if these keys are generated from short (weak) passwords or passwords that can be found in a dictionary.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 allows both providing random uniformly distributed cryptographic keys and generating cryptographic keys from a password supplied by the user.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The risk of guessing authentication strings from hash values transmitted over the network depends on the cryptographic hash function used and the length of the hash value.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 uses the HMAC-SHA-2 authentication protocol for the User-based Security Model (USM).
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP does not use a more secure challenge-handshake authentication protocol.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 (like other SNMP protocol versions) is a stateless protocol, and it has been designed with a minimal amount of interactions between the agent and the manager.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Thus introducing a challenge-response handshake for each command would impose a burden on the agent (and possibly on the network itself) that the protocol designers deemed excessive and unacceptable.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The security deficiencies of all SNMP versions can be mitigated by IPsec authentication and confidentiality mechanisms.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP also may be carried securely over Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS).
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Many SNMP implementations include a type of automatic discovery where a new network component, such as a switch or router, is discovered and polled automatically.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] In SNMPv1 and SNMPv2c, this is done through a *community string* that is transmitted in clear-text to other devices.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Clear-text passwords are a significant security risk.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Once the community string is known outside the organization, it could become the target for an attack.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] To alert administrators of other attempts to glean community strings, SNMP can be configured to pass community-name authentication failure traps.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] If SNMPv2 is used, the issue can be avoided by enabling password encryption on the SNMP agents of network devices.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] The common default configuration for community strings are "public" for read-only access and "private" for read-write.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Because of the well-known defaults, SNMP topped the list of the SANS Institute's Common Default Configuration Issues and was number ten on the SANS Top 10 Most Critical Internet Security Threats for the year 2000.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] System and network administrators frequently do not change these configurations.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] Whether it runs over TCP or UDP, SNMPv1 and v2 are vulnerable to IP spoofing attacks.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] With spoofing, attackers may bypass device access lists in agents that are implemented to restrict SNMP access.
[src:network-telemetry/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 security mechanisms, such as USM or TSM, can prevent spoofing attacks.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Although the term commonly refers to wireless data transfer mechanisms (e.g., using radio, ultrasonic, or infrared systems), it also encompasses data transferred over other media such as a telephone or computer network, optical link or other wired communications like power line carriers.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Many modern telemetry systems take advantage of the low cost and ubiquity of GSM networks by using SMS to receive and transmit telemetry data.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] A *telemeter* is a physical device used in telemetry.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] It consists of a sensor, a transmission path, and a display, recording, or control device.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Electronic devices are widely used in telemetry and can be wireless or hard-wired, analog or digital.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Other technologies are also possible, such as mechanical, hydraulic and optical.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry may be commutated to allow the transmission of multiple data streams in a fixed frame.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] The beginning of industrial telemetry lies in the steam age, although the sensor was not called *telemeter* at that time.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Examples are James Watt's (1736-1819) additions to his steam engines for monitoring from a (near) distance such as the mercury pressure gauge and the fly-ball governor.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In 1889 this led an author in the Institution of Civil Engineers proceedings to suggest that the term for the rangefinder telemeter might be replaced with tacheometer.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In the 1930s use of electrical telemeters grew rapidly.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] The electrical strain gauge was widely used in rocket and aviation research and the radiosonde was invented for meteorological measurements.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] The advent of World War II gave an impetus to industrial development and henceforth many of these telemeters became commercially viable.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Carrying on from rocket research, radio telemetry was used routinely as space exploration got underway.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Spacecraft are in a place where a physical connection is not possible, leaving radio or other electromagnetic waves (such as infrared lasers) as the only viable option for telemetry.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] During crewed space missions it is used to monitor not only parameters of the vehicle, but also the health and life support of the astronauts.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] During the Cold War telemetry found uses in espionage.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] US intelligence found that they could monitor the telemetry from Soviet missile tests by building a telemeter of their own to intercept the radio signals and hence learn a great deal about Soviet capabilities.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemeters are the physical devices used in telemetry.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetering information over wire had its origins in the 19th century.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] One of the first data-transmission circuits was developed in 1845 between the Russian Tsar's Winter Palace and army headquarters.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In 1874, French engineers built a system of weather and snow-depth sensors on Mont Blanc that transmitted real-time information to Paris.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Michalke patented the selsyn, a circuit for sending synchronized rotation information over a distance.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In 1906 a set of seismic stations were built with telemetering to the Pulkovo Observatory in Russia.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In 1912, Commonwealth Edison developed a system of telemetry to monitor electrical loads on its power grid.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] The Panama Canal (completed 1913–1914) used extensive telemetry systems to monitor locks and water levels.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Wireless telemetry made early appearances in the radiosonde, developed concurrently in 1930 by Robert Bureau in France and Pavel Molchanov in Russia.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Molchanov's system modulated temperature and pressure measurements by converting them to wireless Morse code.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] The German V-2 rocket used a system of primitive multiplexed radio signals called "Messina" to report four rocket parameters, but it was so unreliable that Wernher von Braun once claimed it was more useful to watch the rocket through binoculars.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In the US and the USSR, the Messina system was quickly replaced with better systems; in both cases, based on pulse-position modulation (PPM).
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Early Soviet missile and space telemetry systems which were developed in the late 1940s used either PPM (e.g., the Tral telemetry system developed by OKB-MEI) or pulse-duration modulation (e.g., the RTS-5 system developed by NII-885).
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In the United States, early work employed similar systems, but were later replaced by pulse-code modulation (PCM) (for example, in the Mars probe Mariner 4).
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Later Soviet interplanetary probes used redundant radio systems, transmitting telemetry by PCM on a decimeter band and PPM on a centimeter band.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Although the two terms are closely related, telemetry and telematics are used differently depending on the field.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telematics, by contrast, emerged later as a broader, more applied concept that combines telemetry with telecommunications, informatics, and digital fleet platforms.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In short, telemetry is the enabling technology (remote measurement and data transmission), while telematics describes the integrated, digitalized applications that build on telemetry to deliver business, safety, and operational insights.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Weather balloons use telemetry to transmit meteorological data since 1920.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used to transmit drilling mechanics and formation evaluation information uphole, in real time, as a well is drilled.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] These services are known as Measurement while drilling and Logging while drilling.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Information acquired thousands of feet below ground, while drilling, is sent through the drilling hole to the surface sensors and the demodulation software.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] The pressure wave (sana) is translated into useful information after DSP and noise filters.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] This information is used for Formation evaluation, Drilling Optimization, and Geosteering.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used in modern motor racing, allowing race engineers to interpret data collected during a test or race and use it to properly tune the car for optimum performance.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Systems used in series such as Formula One have become advanced to the point where the potential lap time of the car can be calculated, and this time is what the driver is expected to meet.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Examples of measurements on a race car include accelerations (G forces) in three axes, temperature readings, wheel speed, and suspension displacement.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In Formula One, driver input is also recorded so the team can assess driver performance and (in case of an accident) the FIA can determine or rule out driver error as a possible cause.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Later developments include two-way telemetry which allows engineers to update calibrations on the car in real time (even while it is out on the track).
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In Formula One, two-way telemetry surfaced in the early 1990s and consisted of a message display on the dashboard which the team could update.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Its development continued until May 2001, when it was first allowed on the cars.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] By 2002, teams were able to change engine mapping and deactivate engine sensors from the pit while the car was on the track.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] For the 2003 season, the FIA banned two-way telemetry from Formula One; however, the technology may be used in other types of racing or on road cars.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] One way telemetry system has also been applied in R/C racing car to get information by car's sensors like: engine RPM, voltage, temperatures, throttle.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In the transportation industry, a Fleet telematics system is used to provide information about a vehicle or driver's performance by collecting data from on-board sensors, such as a GPS tracking unit or a telematics control unit (TCU).
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] This is undertaken for various reasons ranging from staff compliance monitoring, insurance rating, fuel management to predictive maintenance.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] As part of an Intelligent transportation system, telemetry is used to link traffic counter devices to data recorders to measure traffic flows and vehicle lengths and weights.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used by the railway industry for measuring the health of trackage.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] This permits optimized and focused predictive and preventative maintenance.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Typically this is done with specialized trains, such as the New Measurement Train used in the United Kingdom by Network Rail, which can check for track defects, such as problems with gauge, and deformations in the rail.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Japan uses similar, but quicker trains, nicknamed Doctor Yellow.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Such trains, besides checking the tracks, can also verify whether or not there are any problems with the overhead power supply (catenary), where it is installed.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Dedicated rail inspection companies, such as Sperry Rail, have their own customized rail cars and rail-wheel equipped trucks, that use a variety of methods, including lasers, ultrasound, and induction (measuring resulting magnetic fields from running electricity into rails) to find any defects.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Most activities related to healthy crops and good yields depend on timely availability of weather and soil data.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Therefore, wireless weather stations play a major role in disease prevention and precision irrigation.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Because local micro-climates can vary significantly, such data needs to come from within the crop.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Monitoring stations usually transmit data back by terrestrial radio, although occasionally satellite systems are used.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Solar power is often employed to make the station independent of the power grid.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used in water management, including water quality and stream gauging functions.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Major applications include AMR (automatic meter reading), groundwater monitoring, leak detection in distribution pipelines and equipment surveillance.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Having data available in almost real time allows quick reactions to events in the field.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry control allows engineers to intervene with assets such as pumps and by remotely switching pumps on or off depending on the circumstances.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used in complex systems such as missiles, RPVs, spacecraft, oil rigs, and chemical plants since it allows the automatic monitoring, alerting, and record-keeping necessary for efficient and safe operation.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Space agencies such as NASA, ISRO, the European Space Agency (ESA), and other agencies use telemetry and/or telecommand systems to collect data from spacecraft and satellites.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used in the development of missiles, satellites and aircraft because the system might be destroyed during or after the test.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Engineers need critical system parameters to analyze (and improve) the performance of the system.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In the absence of telemetry, this data would often be unavailable.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used by crewed or uncrewed spacecraft for data transmission.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Distances of more than 25.1 billion kilometers (May 2025) have been covered, e.g., by Voyager 1.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In rocketry, telemetry equipment forms an integral part of the rocket range assets used to monitor the position and health of a launch vehicle to determine range safety flight termination criteria (Range purpose is for public safety).
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Problems include the extreme environment (temperature, acceleration and vibration), the energy supply, antenna alignment and (at long distances, e.g., in spaceflight) signal travel time.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Today nearly every type of aircraft, missiles, or spacecraft carries a wireless telemetry system as it is tested.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Aeronautical mobile telemetry is used for the safety of the pilots and persons on the ground during flight tests.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry from an on-board flight test instrumentation system is the primary source of real-time measurement and status information transmitted during the testing of crewed and uncrewed aircraft.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Intercepted telemetry was an important source of intelligence for the United States and UK when Soviet missiles were tested; for this purpose, the United States operated a listening post in Iran.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Eventually, the Russians discovered the United States intelligence-gathering network and encrypted their missile-test telemetry signals.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry was also a source for the Soviets, who operated listening ships in Cardigan Bay to eavesdrop on UK missile tests performed in the area.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In factories, buildings and houses, energy consumption of systems such as HVAC are monitored at multiple locations; related parameters (e.g., temperature) are sent via wireless telemetry to a central location.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] The information is collected and processed, enabling the most efficient use of energy.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Such systems also facilitate predictive maintenance.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Many resources need to be distributed over wide areas.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is useful in these cases, since it allows the logistics system to channel resources where they are needed, as well as provide security for those assets; principal examples of this are dry goods, fluids, and granular bulk solids.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] This facilitates knowledge of their location, and can record their status and disposition, as when merchandise with barcode labels is scanned through a checkout reader at point-of-sale systems in a retail store.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Stationary or hand-held barcode RFID scanners or Optical reader with remote communications, can be used to expedite inventory tracking and counting in stores, warehouses, shipping terminals, transportation carriers and factories.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Fluids stored in tanks are a principal object of constant commercial telemetry.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used to communicate the variable measurements of flow and tank level sensors detecting fluid movements and/or volumes by pneumatic, hydrostatic, or differential pressure; tank-confined ultrasonic, radar or Doppler effect echoes; or mechanical or magnetic sensors.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry of bulk solids is common for tracking and reporting the volume status and condition of grain and livestock feed bins, powdered or granular food, powders and pellets for manufacturing, sand and gravel, and other granular bulk solids.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] While technology associated with fluid tank monitoring also applies, in part, to granular bulk solids, reporting of overall container weight, or other gross characteristics and conditions, are sometimes required, owing to bulk solids' more complex and variable physical characteristics.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used for patients (biotelemetry) who are at risk of abnormal heart activity, generally in a coronary care unit.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry specialists are sometimes used to monitor many patients within a hospital.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Such patients are outfitted with measuring, recording and transmitting devices.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] A data log can be useful in diagnosis of the patient's condition by doctors.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] An alerting function can alert nurses if the patient is suffering from an acute (or dangerous) condition.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Systems are available in medical-surgical nursing for monitoring to rule out a heart condition, or to monitor a response to antiarrhythmic medications such as amiodarone.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] A new and emerging application for telemetry is in the field of neurophysiology, or neurotelemetry.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Neurophysiology is the study of the central and peripheral nervous systems through the recording of bioelectrical activity, whether spontaneous or stimulated.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In neurotelemetry (NT) the electroencephalogram (EEG) of a patient is monitored remotely by a registered EEG technologist using advanced communication software.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] The goal of neurotelemetry is to recognize a decline in a patient's condition before physical signs and symptoms are present.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Neurotelemetry is synonymous with real-time continuous video EEG monitoring and has application in the epilepsy monitoring unit, neuro ICU, pediatric ICU and newborn ICU.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Due to the labor-intensive nature of continuous EEG monitoring NT is typically done in the larger academic teaching hospitals using in-house programs that include R.EEG Technologists, IT support staff, neurologist and neurophysiologist and monitoring support personnel.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Modern microprocessor speeds, software algorithms and video data compression allow hospitals to centrally record and monitor continuous digital EEGs of multiple critically ill patients simultaneously.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Neurotelemetry and continuous EEG monitoring provides dynamic information about brain function that permits early detection of changes in neurologic status, which is especially useful when the clinical examination is limited.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used to study wildlife, and has been useful for monitoring threatened species at the individual level.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Animals under study can be outfitted with instrumentation tags, which include sensors that measure temperature, diving depth and duration (for marine animals), speed and location (using GPS or Argos packages).
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry tags can give researchers information about animal behavior, functions, and their environment.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] This information is then either stored (with archival tags) or the tags can send (or transmit) their information to a satellite or handheld receiving device.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Capturing and marking wild animals can put them at some risk, so it is important to minimize these impacts.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] At a 2005 workshop in Las Vegas, a seminar noted the introduction of telemetry equipment which would allow vending machines to communicate sales and inventory data to a route truck or to a headquarters.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] This data could be used for a variety of purposes, such as eliminating the need for drivers to make a first trip to see which items needed to be restocked before delivering the inventory.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Retailers also use RFID tags to track inventory and prevent shoplifting.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Most of these tags passively respond to RFID readers (e.g., at the cashier), but active RFID tags are available which periodically transmit location information to a base station.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] A telemetry-based Tracking system is useful for tracking persons and property in law enforcement.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] An ankle collar worn by convicts on probation can warn authorities if a person violates the terms of his or her parole, such as by straying from authorized boundaries or visiting an unauthorized location.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry has also enabled bait cars, where law enforcement can rig a car with cameras and tracking equipment and leave it somewhere they expect it to be stolen.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] When stolen the telemetry equipment reports the location of the vehicle, enabling a Stolen vehicle recovery process where law enforcement can deactivate the engine and lock the doors when it is stopped by responding officers.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In some countries, telemetry is used to measure the amount of electrical energy consumed.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] The electricity meter communicates with a concentrator, and the latter sends the information through GPRS or GSM to the energy provider's server.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is also used for the remote monitoring of substations and their equipment.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] For data transmission, phase line carrier systems operating on frequencies between 30 and 400 kHz are sometimes used.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In falconry, "telemetry" means a small radio transmitter carried by a bird of prey that will allow the bird's owner to track it when it is out of sight.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used in testing hostile environments which are dangerous to humans.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Examples include munitions storage facilities, radioactive sites, volcanoes, deep sea, and outer space.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used in many battery operated wireless systems to inform monitoring personnel when the battery power is reaching a low point and the end item needs fresh batteries.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In the mining industry, telemetry serves two main purposes: the measurement of key parameters from mining equipment and the monitoring of safety practices.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] The information provided by the collection and analysis of key parameters allows for root-cause identification of inefficient operations, unsafe practices and incorrect equipment usage for maximizing productivity and safety.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Further applications of the technology allow for sharing knowledge and best practices across the organization.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In software, telemetry is used to gather data on the use and performance of applications and application components, e.g. how often certain features are used, measurements of start-up time and processing time, hardware, application crashes, and general usage statistics and/or user behavior.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] In some cases, very detailed data is reported like individual window metrics, counts of used features, and individual function timings.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] This kind of telemetry can be useful to software developers to receive data from a wide variety of endpoints that can't possibly all be tested in-house, as well as getting data on the popularity of certain features and whether they should be given priority or be considered for removal.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] Due to concerns about privacy since software telemetry can easily be used to profile users, telemetry in user software is often user choice, commonly presented as an opt-out feature (requiring explicit user action to disable it) or user choice during the software installation process.
[src:network-telemetry/telemetry] As in other telecommunications fields, international standards exist for telemetry equipment and software.
